Note:
==============================================================================
CODEPOINT - Unicode Scalar Value Primitive
==============================================================================

A CodePoint represents one Unicode scalar value in the range
U+0000..U+10FFFF, excluding the surrogate range U+D800..U+DFFF which is
reserved for UTF-16 encoding and never appears in well-formed Unicode
text (Unicode 15.1, section 3.9).

References:
- Unicode Standard 15.1, Chapter 3 (Conformance)
- RFC 3629: UTF-8, a transformation format of ISO 10646
- UAX #44: Unicode Character Database

This module provides:
- CodePoint validation (is_valid, is_surrogate, in_range)
- Classification (letter, digit, whitespace, control, ...)
- Case mapping (to_upper, to_lower, to_titlecase)
- Block and script lookup
- UTF-8 encode / decode (round-trip with byte buffers)

Classification follows the Unicode general-category property. The
v0.0.8.5 baseline implements the ASCII range plus the common-use Latin-1
Supplement directly; codepoints above U+00FF defer to
internal/unicode_tables.runa when its baseline-zero tables are populated
by the v0.2.x generator. Until then, codepoints >= U+0100 are treated
conservatively (e.g. is_letter returns 0). This matches the documented
contract on unicode_tables.runa and never produces unsafe behavior.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/text/codepoint_unicode_tables.runa" as UT

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Constant CP_MAX as Integer is 1114111
Constant CP_SURROGATE_LOW as Integer is 55296
Constant CP_SURROGATE_HIGH as Integer is 57343
Constant CP_REPLACEMENT as Integer is 65533

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION / VALIDITY
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "codepoint_from_u32" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Validates that the integer is a legal Unicode scalar value and
        returns it; returns -1 for out-of-range or surrogate inputs.
        Callers wanting a lossy mapping should substitute the Unicode
        replacement character U+FFFD on rejection.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
        Range check 0..0x10FFFF inclusive, excluding the contiguous
        surrogate block U+D800..U+DFFF.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
        Three comparisons in the cold case, two in the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
        Rejects every non-scalar value, eliminating an entire class of
        Unicode-confusion attacks where surrogates leak into the
        application layer (see CVE-2008-2938 "UTF-7 / surrogate
        smuggling" pattern).
    @End Security_Scope

    If value is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is greater than CP_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is greater than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_LOW:
        If value is less than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_HIGH:
            Return -1
        End If
    End If
    Return value
End Process

Process called "codepoint_to_u32" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the raw 32-bit value of a codepoint. Pre-validated
    Note: codepoints round-trip through this function.
    Return cp
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_valid" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 1 if cp is a valid Unicode scalar value, else 0.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than CP_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_LOW:
        If cp is less than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_HIGH:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_surrogate" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 1 if cp is in the UTF-16 surrogate range.
    If cp is less than CP_SURROGATE_LOW:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than CP_SURROGATE_HIGH:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_ascii" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: 1 if cp is in the ASCII range U+0000..U+007F.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than 127:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "codepoint_is_letter" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns 1 if cp belongs to Unicode general category L* (Lu, Ll,
        Lt, Lm, Lo). Consults the embedded GC range table via
        UT.unicode_general_category which performs binary search.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        ASCII fast path: A-Z and a-z return 1 without consulting the
        table. Beyond ASCII the GC lookup is authoritative.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        ASCII: constant time. Non-ASCII: O(log n) on the GC range count.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Conformant under-approximation only when the bundled curated
        table is in effect. Callers in security-sensitive paths must
        ALSO enforce script-mixing rules separately.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        If cp is greater than or equal to 65:
            If cp is less than or equal to 90:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        If cp is greater than or equal to 97:
            If cp is less than or equal to 122:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Let gc be UT.unicode_general_category(cp)
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LU:
        Return 1
    End If
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LO:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_digit" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if cp has GC == Nd (Decimal_Number). ASCII '0'..'9'
    Note: fast path; everything else consults the GC table.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        If cp is greater than or equal to 48:
            If cp is less than or equal to 57:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Let gc be UT.unicode_general_category(cp)
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_ND:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_uppercase" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if cp has GC == Lu (Uppercase_Letter). ASCII fast
    Note: path, then GC table.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        If cp is greater than or equal to 65:
            If cp is less than or equal to 90:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Let gc be UT.unicode_general_category(cp)
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LU:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_lowercase" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns 1 if cp has GC == Ll (Lowercase_Letter). ASCII fast
    Note: path, then GC table.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        If cp is greater than or equal to 97:
            If cp is less than or equal to 122:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        Return 0
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Let gc be UT.unicode_general_category(cp)
    If gc is equal to UT.GC_LL:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_whitespace" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns 1 for Unicode whitespace per UAX #44 White_Space property.
        Includes the ASCII whitespace family plus the common Unicode
        spaces (NBSP, EM SPACE, ZW SPACE etc.). The full property table
        ships with the table generator; meanwhile the explicit list
        covers the codepoints we need at this bootstrap stage.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Direct comparisons against ASCII (TAB, LF, VT, FF, CR, SPACE),
        NEL (U+0085), NBSP (U+00A0), the U+2000..U+200A range (general
        punctuation spaces), line/paragraph separators (U+2028, U+2029),
        narrow no-break (U+202F), medium math space (U+205F),
        ideographic space (U+3000).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Branchy on Unicode codepoints; ASCII fast path handled first.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Whitespace recognition matters for token boundary correctness;
        the explicit allowlist prevents unexpected normalization holes.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 9:
        If cp is less than or equal to 13:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is equal to 133:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 160:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 8192:
        If cp is less than or equal to 8202:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is equal to 8232:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 8233:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 8239:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 8287:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 12288:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_punctuation" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ASCII punctuation: 0x21-0x2F, 0x3A-0x40, 0x5B-0x60, 0x7B-0x7E.
    If cp is greater than or equal to 33:
        If cp is less than or equal to 47:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 58:
        If cp is less than or equal to 64:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 91:
        If cp is less than or equal to 96:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 123:
        If cp is less than or equal to 126:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_symbol" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ASCII math symbols: + < = > | ~ etc. Latin-1 symbols included.
    If cp is equal to 36:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 43:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 60:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 61:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 62:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 94:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 96:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 124:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 126:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 162:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 163:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 165:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 215:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 247:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_control" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: U+0000..U+001F and U+007F..U+009F per Unicode Cc category.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is less than 32:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is equal to 127:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 128:
        If cp is less than or equal to 159:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "codepoint_is_emoji" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns 1 if cp is in a known emoji range per UTS #51 (Unicode
        Technical Standard Emoji). The set is large and changes per
        Unicode version; this implementation covers the stable base
        emoji blocks (U+1F300..U+1F5FF Misc Symbols and Pictographs,
        U+1F600..U+1F64F Emoticons, U+1F680..U+1F6FF Transport,
        U+1F900..U+1F9FF Supplemental Symbols, U+1FA70..U+1FAFF Symbols
        and Pictographs Extended-A).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Range tests on the documented emoji blocks. Variation selectors,
        regional indicators (U+1F1E6..U+1F1FF) and ZWJ are NOT emoji
        themselves; callers doing emoji-cluster detection should use
        the grapheme primitive instead.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Branchy but small; classifies most production strings as
        non-emoji on the very first test.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Pure classification, no side effects.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is greater than or equal to 127744:
        If cp is less than or equal to 128591:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 128640:
        If cp is less than or equal to 128767:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 129280:
        If cp is less than or equal to 129791:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 129904:
        If cp is less than or equal to 130175:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 127462:
        If cp is less than or equal to 127487:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CASE MAPPING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "codepoint_to_upper" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Simple case mapping per UAX #44: every codepoint maps to at most
        one uppercase codepoint with no length change. Locale-sensitive
        cases (Turkish dotless-I) and length-changing cases (German
        sharp-s -> SS) live in locale.runa per UAX #44 Table 14.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        ASCII fast path. Beyond ASCII, consult the simple-uppercase
        table via binary search; if no entry exists, return cp unchanged.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        ASCII: constant. Otherwise O(log n).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Pure; unmapped inputs returned verbatim.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is less than 0:
        Return cp
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        If cp is greater than or equal to 97:
            If cp is less than or equal to 122:
                Return cp minus 32
            End If
        End If
        Return cp
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Return UT.unicode_simple_uppercase(cp)
End Process

Process called "codepoint_to_lower" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Simple lowercase mapping. ASCII fast path, then table lookup.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return cp
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        If cp is greater than or equal to 65:
            If cp is less than or equal to 90:
                Return cp plus 32
            End If
        End If
        Return cp
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Return UT.unicode_simple_lowercase(cp)
End Process

Process called "codepoint_to_titlecase" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Simple titlecase mapping. For codepoints with no titlecase
    Note: entry, defaults to the uppercase mapping (UAX #44 sec. 5.7.5).
    Note: Digraph titlecase forms (e.g. U+01F1 DZ / U+01F2 Dz) are
    Note: distinguished by the embedded title table when present.
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return cp
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        Return codepoint_to_upper(cp)
    End If
    UT.codepoint_unicode_tables_init()
    Return UT.unicode_simple_titlecase(cp)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BLOCK / SCRIPT LOOKUP
Note: ============================================================================

Constant BLOCK_BASIC_LATIN as Integer is 0
Constant BLOCK_LATIN_1_SUPPLEMENT as Integer is 1
Constant BLOCK_LATIN_EXTENDED_A as Integer is 2
Constant BLOCK_LATIN_EXTENDED_B as Integer is 3
Constant BLOCK_GREEK as Integer is 4
Constant BLOCK_CYRILLIC as Integer is 5
Constant BLOCK_ARABIC as Integer is 6
Constant BLOCK_HEBREW as Integer is 7
Constant BLOCK_DEVANAGARI as Integer is 8
Constant BLOCK_THAI as Integer is 9
Constant BLOCK_HIRAGANA as Integer is 10
Constant BLOCK_KATAKANA as Integer is 11
Constant BLOCK_CJK_UNIFIED as Integer is 12
Constant BLOCK_HANGUL_SYLLABLES as Integer is 13
Constant BLOCK_GENERAL_PUNCTUATION as Integer is 14
Constant BLOCK_SUPPLEMENTARY as Integer is 15
Constant BLOCK_UNKNOWN as Integer is 99

Process called "codepoint_block" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Maps a codepoint to its Unicode block identifier. Blocks are
        contiguous ranges defined by the Unicode standard (Blocks.txt).
        Returns BLOCK_UNKNOWN for unmapped ranges in the v0.0.8.5
        baseline.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Range tests against the most common Unicode blocks. Order is
        ascending codepoint so early returns short-circuit ASCII.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Linear branch chain; ASCII fast path is the first comparison.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Pure classification.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is less than 0:
        Return BLOCK_UNKNOWN
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        Return BLOCK_BASIC_LATIN
    End If
    If cp is less than 256:
        Return BLOCK_LATIN_1_SUPPLEMENT
    End If
    If cp is less than 384:
        Return BLOCK_LATIN_EXTENDED_A
    End If
    If cp is less than 592:
        Return BLOCK_LATIN_EXTENDED_B
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 880:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1023:
            Return BLOCK_GREEK
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 1024:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1279:
            Return BLOCK_CYRILLIC
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 1424:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1535:
            Return BLOCK_HEBREW
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 1536:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1791:
            Return BLOCK_ARABIC
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 2304:
        If cp is less than or equal to 2431:
            Return BLOCK_DEVANAGARI
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 3584:
        If cp is less than or equal to 3711:
            Return BLOCK_THAI
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 8192:
        If cp is less than or equal to 8303:
            Return BLOCK_GENERAL_PUNCTUATION
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 12352:
        If cp is less than or equal to 12447:
            Return BLOCK_HIRAGANA
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 12448:
        If cp is less than or equal to 12543:
            Return BLOCK_KATAKANA
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 19968:
        If cp is less than or equal to 40959:
            Return BLOCK_CJK_UNIFIED
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 44032:
        If cp is less than or equal to 55215:
            Return BLOCK_HANGUL_SYLLABLES
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than 65535:
        Return BLOCK_SUPPLEMENTARY
    End If
    Return BLOCK_UNKNOWN
End Process

Constant SCRIPT_LATIN as Integer is 0
Constant SCRIPT_GREEK as Integer is 1
Constant SCRIPT_CYRILLIC as Integer is 2
Constant SCRIPT_ARABIC as Integer is 3
Constant SCRIPT_HEBREW as Integer is 4
Constant SCRIPT_DEVANAGARI as Integer is 5
Constant SCRIPT_THAI as Integer is 6
Constant SCRIPT_HAN as Integer is 7
Constant SCRIPT_HIRAGANA as Integer is 8
Constant SCRIPT_KATAKANA as Integer is 9
Constant SCRIPT_HANGUL as Integer is 10
Constant SCRIPT_COMMON as Integer is 11
Constant SCRIPT_UNKNOWN as Integer is 99

Process called "codepoint_script" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Maps a codepoint to its Unicode Script property per UAX #24.
        Scripts and blocks are related but not identical: e.g. Latin
        script spans Basic Latin, Latin-1 Supplement, Latin Extended-A,
        Latin Extended-B. The SCRIPT_COMMON value covers shared
        punctuation and whitespace.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Same range tests as codepoint_block but folded into the script
        hierarchy.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Linear branches; ASCII path early.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Critical for IDN and identifier-mixing detection; this rough
        mapping is sufficient for the bootstrap and will be replaced
        by the generated UAX #24 table in v0.2.x.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is less than 0:
        Return SCRIPT_UNKNOWN
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        Note: Basic Latin: letters are Latin script, others Common
        If cp is greater than or equal to 65:
            If cp is less than or equal to 90:
                Return SCRIPT_LATIN
            End If
        End If
        If cp is greater than or equal to 97:
            If cp is less than or equal to 122:
                Return SCRIPT_LATIN
            End If
        End If
        Return SCRIPT_COMMON
    End If
    If cp is less than 592:
        Return SCRIPT_LATIN
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 880:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1023:
            Return SCRIPT_GREEK
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 1024:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1279:
            Return SCRIPT_CYRILLIC
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 1424:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1535:
            Return SCRIPT_HEBREW
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 1536:
        If cp is less than or equal to 1791:
            Return SCRIPT_ARABIC
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 2304:
        If cp is less than or equal to 2431:
            Return SCRIPT_DEVANAGARI
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 3584:
        If cp is less than or equal to 3711:
            Return SCRIPT_THAI
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 12352:
        If cp is less than or equal to 12447:
            Return SCRIPT_HIRAGANA
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 12448:
        If cp is less than or equal to 12543:
            Return SCRIPT_KATAKANA
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 19968:
        If cp is less than or equal to 40959:
            Return SCRIPT_HAN
        End If
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 44032:
        If cp is less than or equal to 55215:
            Return SCRIPT_HANGUL
        End If
    End If
    Return SCRIPT_UNKNOWN
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: UTF-8 ENCODE / DECODE
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "codepoint_utf8_byte_length" takes cp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Returns the number of bytes (1, 2, 3, or 4) required to encode
        cp in UTF-8, or -1 if cp is not a valid scalar value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        RFC 3629 layout:
            0x0000..0x007F -> 1 byte
            0x0080..0x07FF -> 2 bytes
            0x0800..0xFFFF -> 3 bytes (excluding surrogates)
            0x10000..0x10FFFF -> 4 bytes
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Three branches.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Rejects surrogates and out-of-range inputs.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cp is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is less than 2048:
        Return 2
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_LOW:
        If cp is less than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_HIGH:
            Return -1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is less than 65536:
        Return 3
    End If
    If cp is greater than CP_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "codepoint_to_utf8_bytes" takes cp as Integer, buffer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Encodes cp as UTF-8 into buffer starting at offset. Returns the
        number of bytes written, or -1 on invalid codepoint or null
        buffer. The buffer is a raw allocation - caller must ensure at
        least 4 bytes of slack from offset.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Bit-pack per RFC 3629:
          1-byte: 0xxxxxxx
          2-byte: 110xxxxx 10xxxxxx
          3-byte: 1110xxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
          4-byte: 11110xxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Branch on length category; each write is O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Surrogates and >U+10FFFF rejected up front. The continuation
        bytes are always proper 10xxxxxx, so no overlong forms are
        produced.
    @End Security_Scope

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset, cp)
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is less than 2048:
        Let b0 be 192 plus (cp divided by 64)
        Let cp_low6 be cp minus ((cp divided by 64) multiplied by 64)
        Let b1 be 128 plus cp_low6
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset, b0)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset plus 1, b1)
        Return 2
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_LOW:
        If cp is less than or equal to CP_SURROGATE_HIGH:
            Return -1
        End If
    End If
    If cp is less than 65536:
        Let high4 be cp divided by 4096
        Let rem12 be cp minus (high4 multiplied by 4096)
        Let mid6 be rem12 divided by 64
        Let low6 be rem12 minus (mid6 multiplied by 64)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset, 224 plus high4)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset plus 1, 128 plus mid6)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset plus 2, 128 plus low6)
        Return 3
    End If
    If cp is greater than CP_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let high3 be cp divided by 262144
    Let rem18 be cp minus (high3 multiplied by 262144)
    Let mid6a be rem18 divided by 4096
    Let rem12b be rem18 minus (mid6a multiplied by 4096)
    Let mid6b be rem12b divided by 64
    Let low6 be rem12b minus (mid6b multiplied by 64)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset, 240 plus high3)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset plus 1, 128 plus mid6a)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset plus 2, 128 plus mid6b)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buffer, offset plus 3, 128 plus low6)
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "codepoint_from_utf8_bytes" takes buffer as Integer, offset as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Decodes a single UTF-8 codepoint starting at offset in buffer.
        Returns the codepoint on success, or -1 on invalid encoding /
        truncation. The number of bytes consumed is encoded in the
        upper 32 bits to allow returning two values from a single
        Integer: result = (bytes_consumed shifted_left 32) | codepoint.
        Callers can extract via integer division and modulo.
        For convenience, codepoint_decode_length and codepoint_decode_value
        are provided as separate accessors below.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Lead-byte classification per RFC 3629, with overlong and
        surrogate rejection. The encoder is the inverse.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Branchy but constant per character (max 4 byte loads).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Strict RFC 3629 conformance: every malformed sequence yields
        -1 rather than a substituted replacement, so callers can
        distinguish "bad input" from "valid U+FFFD".
    @End Security_Scope

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If offset is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If offset is greater than or equal to length:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset)
    If b0 is less than 128:
        Note: 1-byte: codepoint = b0, length = 1
        Let result be (1 multiplied by 4294967296) plus b0
        Return result
    End If
    If b0 is less than 194:
        Return -1
    End If
    If b0 is less than 224:
        Note: 2-byte
        If (offset plus 1) is greater than or equal to length:
            Return -1
        End If
        Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset plus 1)
        If b1 is less than 128:
            Return -1
        End If
        If b1 is greater than or equal to 192:
            Return -1
        End If
        Let cp_a be ((b0 minus 192) multiplied by 64) plus (b1 minus 128)
        Let result_a be (2 multiplied by 4294967296) plus cp_a
        Return result_a
    End If
    If b0 is less than 240:
        Note: 3-byte
        If (offset plus 2) is greater than or equal to length:
            Return -1
        End If
        Let b1c be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset plus 1)
        Let b2c be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset plus 2)
        If b1c is less than 128:
            Return -1
        End If
        If b1c is greater than or equal to 192:
            Return -1
        End If
        If b2c is less than 128:
            Return -1
        End If
        If b2c is greater than or equal to 192:
            Return -1
        End If
        Note: Overlong check: E0 needs b1 in A0-BF (>=160)
        If b0 is equal to 224:
            If b1c is less than 160:
                Return -1
            End If
        End If
        Note: Surrogate check: ED needs b1 in 80-9F (<160)
        If b0 is equal to 237:
            If b1c is greater than or equal to 160:
                Return -1
            End If
        End If
        Let cp_b be ((b0 minus 224) multiplied by 4096) plus ((b1c minus 128) multiplied by 64)
        Set cp_b to cp_b plus (b2c minus 128)
        Let result_b be (3 multiplied by 4294967296) plus cp_b
        Return result_b
    End If
    If b0 is greater than 244:
        Return -1
    End If
    Note: 4-byte
    If (offset plus 3) is greater than or equal to length:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let d1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset plus 1)
    Let d2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset plus 2)
    Let d3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buffer, offset plus 3)
    If d1 is less than 128:
        Return -1
    End If
    If d1 is greater than or equal to 192:
        Return -1
    End If
    If d2 is less than 128:
        Return -1
    End If
    If d2 is greater than or equal to 192:
        Return -1
    End If
    If d3 is less than 128:
        Return -1
    End If
    If d3 is greater than or equal to 192:
        Return -1
    End If
    Note: Overlong: F0 needs d1 in 90-BF
    If b0 is equal to 240:
        If d1 is less than 144:
            Return -1
        End If
    End If
    Note: Out of range: F4 needs d1 in 80-8F (<144)
    If b0 is equal to 244:
        If d1 is greater than or equal to 144:
            Return -1
        End If
    End If
    Let cp_c be ((b0 minus 240) multiplied by 262144) plus ((d1 minus 128) multiplied by 4096)
    Set cp_c to cp_c plus ((d2 minus 128) multiplied by 64)
    Set cp_c to cp_c plus (d3 minus 128)
    Let result_c be (4 multiplied by 4294967296) plus cp_c
    Return result_c
End Process

Process called "codepoint_decode_length" takes packed as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extracts the bytes-consumed count from a codepoint_from_utf8_bytes result.
    If packed is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return packed divided by 4294967296
End Process

Process called "codepoint_decode_value" takes packed as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extracts the codepoint value from a codepoint_from_utf8_bytes result.
    If packed is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let length_field be packed divided by 4294967296
    Return packed minus (length_field multiplied by 4294967296)
End Process
